So given the constrained supply of Tesla vehicles, those two can't just go out and update their fleet with a bunch of new Model 3's

This is a major competitive advantage for $TSLA as their cars are naturally scarce but the company also controls 100% of distribution

Just take note of the major drivers of cost savings for a $TSLA ride hailing network: maintenance, depreciation, and fuel savings

Aside from operating at a loss, those aren't variables $UBER and $LYFT can change without having actual Tesla vehicles in their network https://t.co/axkKXmshLd

But aside from that, the vertical integration of $TSLA through manufacturing, insurance, data, and then a consumer app would be very dangerous for $UBER and $LYFT

The cost implications could quickly turn those two into second rate networks that mostly rent bikes and e-scooters

In order to do ride sharing as laid out in the @ARKInvest research note, $TSLA needs to reserve a % of their production capacity for a hailing network

https://t.co/l9oXJ3N8WQ

The key resistance against this is the lack of capacity to build cars for people that want to do ride sharing

Given the current profile of $TSLA owners it's hard to see the Tesla crowd participating in a ride share network
